																		The Laughing Tree
															</div>
				<div class="info">
					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/granite-mask" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(5147952); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=5147952&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610202623" alt="Granite Mask" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=5147952)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/granite-mask" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(5147952); return false;" >Granite Mask</a></span> <span class="odate time_1609634430 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">03 Jan 2021 00:40</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-4860645">
									

<p><strong>Seeking Greenlights:</strong> Yes</p>
<p><strong>Page Type:</strong> SCP Article</p>
<p><strong>Genre (Optional):</strong> Campfire Horror, Emotional</p>
<p><strong>Page Layout (Optional):</strong> Containment procedure, description of the entity's feeding ritual, 2 interviews with a survivor of the ritual, and 1 interview with an involved camp staff-member.</p>
<p><strong>Elevator Pitch:</strong> The Laughing Tree is a memetic entity rooted within an old wooden-tent campground commonly used by scouts or youth groups. The tree convinces children to tie one of their own to its trunk, and, when secured, it carves their name into its bark. These victims live on to help the tree find new prey, and laugh at the pain and suffering it inflicts.</p>
<p><strong>Central Narrative:</strong> A low-level foundation member calls attention to this entity after his child is almost tied to the tree. Previously, he laughed the tale off as a &quot;camp story&quot; to several co-workers. He is told to bring in his child for questioning.</p>
<div class="collapsible-block">
<div class="collapsible-block-folded"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">+&nbsp;show&nbsp;block</a></div>
<div class="collapsible-block-unfolded" style="display:none">
<div class="collapsible-block-unfolded-link"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">–&nbsp;hide&nbsp;block</a></div>
<div class="collapsible-block-content">
<p>The first interiew is short. After providing a cover story, the investigator asks what happened. Emotionally dead, the kid replies, &quot;you'll just laugh at me..&quot;</p>
<p>The second interview occurs after the parent tries to console their child. The parent tries to help answer preliminary questions by describing camp activities. At the mention of knot-tying, the child's face goes pale.</p>
<p>The interviewer asks why the child didn't want to attend camp. Instead of answering he makes a small digression about how he felt sorry for a spider that another kid burned. The parent interrupts and describes his child as socially isolated and wonders if this behavior is related to the nature of his work.</p>
<p>Eventually, the child describes what happened, One-by-one belongings of other scouts find their way to his tent. Camp staff approach him and ask about thefts. The child tries to explain that he didn't take them, but they laugh at him. He runs. Then they, the scouts, surround him with knot-tying ropes and force him toward the *tree*. He tries and fails to escape, as the scouts laugh at him. The laughter grows louder.. and deeper until he realizes that it's coming from behind. And then, the laughter stops.</p>
<p>The investigator asks what changed. The child looks down, and cries.</p>
<p>A third interview takes place with a camp staff-member and former victim. He laughs at suffering he causes, and his own.</p>
<p><strong>Hook/Attention-Grabber:</strong> Laughter, not as a coping mechanism but as something to be feared.</p>
<p><strong>Additional Notes:</strong> Besides names, the tree also has &quot;HA&quot; etched into its bark, and it is disgusted by urine.</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>

