			<div class="content" id="post-content-4861152">
									

<p>I like this tree. It's got that cool mix of campfire story and actual hazard.</p>
<p>1) The big question is how the tree hides the fact that a child died while under relatively close supervision. You're going to have to explain what appears to be a kidnapping to the authorities (presumably the child's belongings are still at camp) while no one is filming. That's something that can shut down a camp and create a lot of problems.</p>
<p>2) The tree is capable of manipulating objects? A better way of doing it would be that a kid drops them off at the tent in question and then forgets about it. However, I'd point out that the counselors are going to point out that the tents are not exactly secure; that lack of security is why you see so many pranks during those camping events. It also means that just as anything can be stolen from them, so is it easy to frame someone.</p>
<p>All of this means that the tree has more than just a fancy way of being invisible but also has a level of mind control going on as well.</p>
<p>3) If not all of its victims are acceptable, then you need to tell why it lets some of them go. The fewer mysteries the better.</p>
<p>4) The part about the spider was a nice touch, especially as the kid has a reason to feel empathy with spider.</p>
<p>5) The Hook: You need to add that to the Central Narrative. A &quot;hook&quot; is why we should basically care for it, and what makes it unique, or even works into the greater universe; you have a great hook in that this is a situation where laughter becomes something to be feared, which is sort of cool.</p>
<p>Again, a great idea, it just has some minor problems.</p>

							</div>

								
