			<div class="content" id="post-content-4861205">
									

<p>Thanks for the feedback!</p>
<p>I have a few ideas to address these problems, but some of them are unpolished.</p>
<div class="collapsible-block">
<div class="collapsible-block-folded"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">+&nbsp;show&nbsp;block</a></div>
<div class="collapsible-block-unfolded" style="display:none">
<div class="collapsible-block-unfolded-link"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">-&nbsp;hide&nbsp;block</a></div>
<div class="collapsible-block-content">
<p>1) I'm thinking that the tree doesn't <em>physically</em> consume the child during the ritual. This would prevent alarm from camp disappearances. But that doesn't mean there aren't more concrete consequences. One of the post-notes would mention that a child from each camp period would suddenly disappear days or weeks after attending camp. Disappearances like this are often written off as runaways or kidnappings and would largely be unattributed to the camp.</p>
<p>Alternatively, the tree could replace the kids with something else, but I think either option is best left unexplained.</p>
<p>2) I have two ideas for object manipulation. The tree could use memetic influence to have kids do the framing themselves, or it could use its roots to physically move things. This may allow other incidents such as tripping kids near the victim. I'm not sure what would be better, as the root network might open up a can of worms, but memetic influence seems to write away the cruelty as &quot;not their fault.&quot; I kind of like the idea of people doing horrible things under the right circumstances.</p>
<p>3) The tree is disgusted by urine, ending the ritual/laughter. I want to convey that the kid wet himself without actually saying it. I feel like this could be horrifying &amp; funny depending on the audience, which also plays into the whole &quot;laughing it off&quot; theme.</p>
<p>4) Thanks! :) I have some ideas for connecting this moment to the rest of the story.</p>
<p>5) I think I assumed that the hook had to be in the beginning of the article (i.e. the containment procedure). Falling back to #3, the audience would wonder why human urine is involved at all and jump back to the beginning to make the connection. But the first interview might be a better hook for the overall narrative and laughing trope.</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<p>EDIT: Shortened my reply.</p>

