<p>Hi RED, Thank you for the review.</p>
<p>Some concept details couldn't be included since I hit the 400-word limit, but many of your points are valid. I'll address them below.</p>
<div class="collapsible-block">
<div class="collapsible-block-folded"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">+&nbsp;show&nbsp;block</a></div>
<div class="collapsible-block-unfolded" style="display:none">
<div class="collapsible-block-unfolded-link"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">–&nbsp;hide&nbsp;block</a></div>
<div class="collapsible-block-content">
<div class="blockquote">
<p>how exactly does the tree convince you to tie someone up?</p>
</div>
It targets socially isolated kids. It frames the victim for theft. And this part was removed, but the tree also trips aggressive kids while they are near this victim. (Also, some members of the camp staff are in on it, as they are former victims)
<div class="blockquote">
<p>does the tree itself carve the child's name? or do the children do it?</p>
</div>
The tree does it.
<div class="blockquote">
<p>how exactly do these victims live on to help the tree? do they still have any free will? what happens when they leave the camp? what exactly happens after ones name is carved?- in the immediate future?</p>
</div>
They leave with a warped sense of empathy, and enjoy watching other kids go through the same ordeal. Some of them return as camp staff and help &quot;stoke the fire&quot; by laughing at the victim when he asks for help or by putting a stolen item back when the victim tries to get rid of it.
<div class="blockquote">
<p>why the child didn't want to go to camp</p>
</div>
Prior to camp, he was already socially isolated among peers.
<div class="blockquote">
<p>what exactly happened after he got tied to the tree.</p>
</div>
The interviewed child is <em>not</em> tied to the tree. He manages to stop its influence by wetting himself. One particular goal of this piece is to show that those that escape still feel shame and have a normal sense of empathy. The interviewed camp staff, however, was tied to the tree in his youth, and now laughs at the experience while disregarding the pain of others.
<div class="blockquote">
<p>parts of the narrative that show the parent stepped in?</p>
</div>
The parent is not present at the camp. He only steps in during the interview, when his child becomes distraught or to answer the few questions he can.
<hr />
<p>Regarding your point about how the tree is called to the Foundation's attention. It's true that this is a little lacking. But I think that the foundation would be interested in rumors/tales that allude to a possible SCP entity. Perhaps the investigation department checks the background for names written on the tree and finds a pattern of anti-social behavior among them. Is there something in SCP that could possible help with this point? like a signature for a nefarious group or individual?</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>

